        <options>
            <option letter="a">Government reform</option>
            <option letter="b">Scandals and corruption</option>
            <option letter="c">Progressive policies</option>
            <option letter="d">Labor support</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Warren G. Harding's presidency (1921-1923) was marked by multiple scandals and corruption, most notably the Teapot Dome scandal. While his administration promoted "normalcy" and business interests, it was tarnished by the criminal behavior of his appointees, including Interior Secretary Albert Fall and Attorney General Harry Daugherty, making his presidency primarily remembered for corruption.</explanation>
